The paper proposes a new randomized matrix that can be used to approximate the multiplication of a large matrix with a Gaussian matrix. This technique has applications in various areas of computer science, including nonnegative matrix factorization and support vector machines. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), which deals with the study of communication systems and their properties. Other likely sub-categories include cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.NA (Numerical Analysis), and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
